CILITY AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES



The SABIC plant is located along the Ohio River in Washington, WV, about eight miles south of Parkersburg, WV.  It was built in 1957 and currently employs about 125 people in the Mid-Ohio Valley.  The plant manufactures thermoplastic resins and pellets.  Our products are used in the construction, automotive, medical, electronics, computer, and appliance industries, to name a few.  

The site is also home to a Technology Center, where SABIC conducts advanced research in polymer technology.  



The Washington, WV plant uses two chemicals that are regulated under the EPA's Risk Management Program (RMP) rule: acrylonitrile, a regulated toxic substance; and, 1,3-butadiene, a regulated flammable substance.  Acrylonitrile and 1,3-butadiene are raw materials used to manufacture our products. 



0.4 GENERAL ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM/ CHEMICAL-SPECIFIC PREVENTION STEPS



SABIC has implemented a comprehensive Process Safety Management (or PSM) program to prevent accidental releases of highly hazardous chemicals.  PSM is an integral part of working safely at SABIC facilities.  PSM ensures that proper safety information is in place; operating procedures are followed; chemical hazards are identified; employees and contractors are trained; and, critical equipment is properly inspected and maintained.  PSM satisfies the accidental release prevention program requirements of the RMP.



Some of the many, specific safety features to prevent a chemical accident include:

- Computer-controlled Safety Instrumented Systems (SIS) on the butadiene latex reactors to ensure that any deviations from the intended operating conditions are immediately identified and corrected;

- Safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error which could lead to a storage tank overfill;

- Secondary containment dikes around storage tanks to contain a spill;

- Butadiene and acrylonitrile gas sensors to detect and warn of a release;

- Spill containmen

t around acrylonitrile railcars at the unloading station to mitigate the impact of a leak;

- Acrylonitrile railcar and butadiene barge and railcar unloading operations are continuously attended by operators who have received specialized training in US Department of Transportation (DOT) requirements;

- Extensive safety information about the processes available to employees;

- Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions;

- Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work practices;

- Maintenance programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability - includes equipment testing and inspection;

- Compliance auditing to ensure standards are being followed;

- A safety procedure to review proposed plant modifications before they are implemented for possible hazards;

- Safety pre-qualification for all contractors;

- Safety reviews prior to startup of our processes; and,

- Safety systems that control hazards during special operations such as welding. 



 0.5 FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY



The Washington, WV site has an outstanding record of accident prevention, which demonstrates its commitment to public and worker safety.  Even minor incidents are investigated to identify what went wrong and to learn how to prevent future occurrences.



The RMP requires that all incidents involving regulated chemicals that resulted in any off-site impact or significant on-site impacts are reported in this document.  During the previous five-year period, there were no such accidents at the Washington site.  



